         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1958a"/><citedRange>142</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1977b"/><citedRange>175</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... there (is) a heap [that is] higher than mount Vipula ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>47</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>294</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... and why the desire for rebirth was evoked? Why ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... a birth with the name ... . The Dharmavṛddhi [prosperity of the Law] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the (gi)ver (of gifts) enjoyed ... 3. Why ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:meunier2013"/><citedRange>160</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... would I (hear the Law?)? I who have treated badly (others) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the Buddhalords (appear) with difficulty (in the world) like the Udumbara flower ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... I ... those people riding on steeds in (the city of) Śrāvasti ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the teacher ... in those individual hells ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... a beautiful woman (is) clinging to ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... now they are falling from mount Sumeru ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... they (collec)ted (fruits?) of trees belonging to the community ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... one heap of meat now ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="philcomment">The verso is in prose, the recto in verse.</note><note type="remarks">The left part of a leaf including the string hole space in lines 3 and 4.</note><note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment"><hi>ṣim</hi> is the end of a 1.sg. optative, probably <hi>klyoṣim</hi> 'may I hear', less likely are <hi>wleṣim</hi> 'may I work' and <hi>wināṣim</hi> 'may I worship'.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment"><hi>mant</hi> is probably the end of a 3.pl. middle preterite I form from a root ending in -<hi>m</hi>, such as <hi>sāmā</hi>- 'to collect' or <hi>kāmā</hi>- 'to bring'. At the end <hi>ka</hi> is the beginning of a term being fem.pl.; since <hi>karkes</hi> 'branches' is most likely masculine, it does not fit.</note></p>
         </div>
